{"parentUuid":"b690be9c-b7fe-4aab-921a-fb1486e70621","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a85079ae82257d010","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcsojW5QQRxxKdZr2pVft","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Eot1no1Vsb5MevANZgmPXb","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"c:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.pipeline\\debug-notes.md","content":"# Debug notes\n\n## 2026-07-10 — CI remediation: make required pipeline-ci contexts green (branch `ci-fix/required-checks-green`)\n\nOperator-authorized remediation (not a pipeline-loop stage). Goal: make the\nrequired `pipeline-ci` contexts green on a dedicated branch off `origin/main`\n(commit ef3fb3f) so PRs to main can merge. All failures were pre-existing on main.\nReproduced each from the referenced runs (main 29049988187, PR #4 29068770309)\nand, where tooling was available locally (Docker + terraform + the `.venv`), by\nrunning the CI's own scanner/test commands.\n\n### 1. build-and-test — 5 test failures\n\nReproduced via `gh run view 29049988187 --log-failed` (pytest short summary: 5 failed).\nThree distinct root causes:\n\n- **Seed-script `ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'src'` (3 tests:**\n  `test_seed_api_key_script.py::{test_seed_api_key_script_persists_only_the_hash,\n  test_admin_flag_sets_scope}` and\n  `test_usage_export_endpoint.py::test_export_seeded_dast_key_can_call_the_export`).\n  Root cause: `scripts/seed_api_key.py` does `from src... import ...` at module load.\n  When it runs as a subprocess (`python scripts/seed_api_key.py`), Python puts the\n  script's own dir (`scripts/`) on `sys.path[0]`, NOT the repo root, so `import src`\n  fails whenever the package isn't installed — which is exactly CI's case\n  (`poetry install --no-root`). Under pytest it works because a root conftest gets\n  the repo root on the path; the subprocess doesn't inherit that.\n  Reproduced locally: `python scripts/seed_api_key.py --label x` → `No module named 'src'`.\n  Fix: prepend the repo root to `sys.path` in the script before importing `src`\n  (self-contained regardless of install mode). Verified: the import now resolves\n  (fails later only on third-party deps absent from my system Python — not `src`).\n\n- **DAST doc test** `test_dast_context_documented.py::test_bearer_split_token_auth_context_is_documented`.\n  Root cause: the test asserts both `mtr_live` AND `Bearer` appear in\n  `.pipeline/plan.md` OR `docs/system_architecture.md`. `.pipeline/` is git-ignored\n  (never in CI's checkout), and `docs/system_architecture.md` had `mtr_live` but not\n  `Bearer` → passed locally (untracked plan.md present) / failed in CI. Evidence:\n  `git grep -l Bearer HEAD -- docs/` did not list system_architecture.md.\n  Fix: document the real auth context in the Auth section of\n  `docs/system_architecture.md` (`Authorization: Bearer mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>`).\n  Verified locally: `pytest tests/test_dast_context_documented.py` → 1 passed.\n\n- **Export p95 perf test** `test_usage_export_perf.py::…3000ms_budget…`.\n  Root cause: machine-load-sensitive wall-clock p95 assertion; CI logs show p95\n  5674ms vs the 3000ms budget (the budget was set against ~2.0s on a quiet host).\n  It rode the unfiltered pytest job. Per the task guidance (mark rather than loosen),\n  marked it `@pytest.mark.perf`, registered the marker in `pyproject.toml`, and\n  changed the CI pytest step to `-m \"not perf\"`. Budget unchanged; the test still\n  runs on a quiet/dedicated host. Verified locally: `-m \"not perf\"` deselects exactly\n  that test; `--collect-only -m perf` → 1/185 collected (only the intended test).\n  Coverage margin (CI was 87.95% with it) is preserved — the export path stays\n  covered by test_usage_export_endpoint.py / _service.py.\n\n### 2. sast — Semgrep `avoid-sqlalchemy-text` (2 blocking)\n\nReproduced locally with the CI command (`semgrep scan --config auto --severity ERROR\n--error .`) → 2 findings in `src/repositories/usage_repo.py:129,175`. Analysis: both\n`text(f\"… {where_clause} …\")` sites interpolate ONLY `where_clause`, which\n`_export_filter_clause_and_params` builds exclusively from fixed literal fragments\n(chosen by which filters are present); all filter values travel as bound params. No\ncaller input reaches the SQL string — a false positive, not a SQLi sink. A rewrite to\nSQLAlchemy Core would be a redesign (out of scope for debugging). Fix: targeted inline\n`# nosemgrep: <rule-id>` on each `text(...)` match line + a justification comment.\nFirst attempt placed the comment block ABOVE the match (not honored — Semgrep only\nhonors nosemgrep on the match's own line); corrected to put it on the `text(` line.\nVerified locally: `semgrep … --error .` → 0 findings, exit 0.\n\n### 3. deps — OSV step exit 127\n\nReproduced: the step used `osv-scanner … scan --lockfile-scan-mode=all -r /src`, but\nunpinned `:latest` floated from v1 to v2.4.0 and REMOVED that flag → `flag provided\nbut not defined: -lockfile-scan-mode` → exit 127. Fix: correct to the v2 command\n`scan source --recursive /src` and pin the image by digest\n(`@sha256:5116601…`, the same digest CI's linux runner pulls) per the workflow's\nsupply-chain posture. Running the fixed command surfaced a real, sub-floor finding the\n127 had masked: `pytest` (dev) 8.3.4, PYSEC-2026-1845 / GHSA-6w46-j5rx-g56g, **CVSS\n6.8** — BELOW the workflow's documented B6 \"CVSS >= 7.0 fails\" floor, and pytest is a\ndev-only dependency (never in the prod image). osv-scanner exits 1 on ANY finding, so\nthe >= 7.0 floor is expressed via the committed `osv-scanner.toml` waiver contract:\nadded an `[[IgnoredVulns]]` entry with justification + `ignoreUntil`. NOT bumped to\npytest 9.0.3 (major bump; pytest-asyncio/-cov compat risk across the whole suite;\ndisproportionate for a sub-floor dev advisory). Verified locally: `scan source -r`\nloads `osv-scanner.toml`, filters the finding, and exits 0 (\"No issues found\").\n\n### 4. containers-iac — Trivy + Checkov\n\n**Trivy (misconfig)**: reproduced 27 HIGH/CRITICAL infra findings. Fixes (real):\n- AWS-0104 (unrestricted egress, 12): scoped ALB egress to the VPC CIDR:8000; task\n  egress to the VPC CIDR (RDS/Redis) + a narrowed 443/tcp internet rule; rds/redis\n  egress to the VPC CIDR. CIDRs (not peer SG ids) avoid circular SG references.\n- AWS-0052 (ALB drop invalid headers, 3): `drop_invalid_header_fields = true`.\n- AWS-0095 (SNS unencrypted, 3): `kms_master_key_id = \"alias/aws/sns\"`.\n- AWS-0132 (S3 not CMK, 6): new `aws_kms_key.observability` (rotation on) wired into\n  both audit-archive + canary buckets' SSE; canary bucket had no SSE at all before.\nDocumented accepted-risk inline ignores (with justification):\n- AWS-0053 (public ALB): internet-facing ALB is the designed architecture.\n- AWS-0104 on the task SG's 443 rule: tasks need outbound HTTPS via NAT (ECR/Secrets\n  Manager/CloudWatch/X-Ray/Sentry); no VPC endpoints in scope; egress is 443-only.\n- AWS-0136 (SNS not CMK — newly surfaced after the AWS-0095 fix): the alert topic is\n  encrypted with the AWS-managed SNS key and carries only operational alarm data; a\n  CMK would need a bespoke CloudWatch-publish key policy (get it wrong → silent alert\n  loss). Deferred hardening.\nVerified locally: `trivy fs --scanners misconfig --exit-code 1 --severity HIGH,CRITICAL\n/src/infra` → exit 0. (A full-tree `trivy fs` crashes locally only on my populated\n`.venv/`, which CI's fresh checkout doesn't have — not a finding.)\n\n**Checkov**: NEVER ran in prior CI — the Trivy step failed first in the same job and\nshort-circuited it, so the task's \"12 CRITICAL AWS-0104\" was actually Trivy's AVD IDs.\nWith Trivy fixed, Checkov ran for the first time: 48 failed checks (~33 unique),\nacross CloudFront/WAF, RDS, S3, KMS, logging. Fixed the cheap single-attribute wins in\n`.tf` (RDS IAM-auth / auto-minor-upgrade / CW-log-export / Performance-Insights-CMK /\ncopy-tags-to-snapshot; ALB deletion protection; S3 canary versioning; CKV_SECRET_6\ninline skip on the `random_password`-interpolated DB URL false positive). The residual\nfalse-positive / design / scope findings are waived in a committed, per-ID-justified\n`.checkov.yaml` (not a blanket soft-fail). A dedicated IaC-hardening pass (cross-region\nDR, WAF/CloudFront logging, CMK log groups, secret rotation, enhanced monitoring) is\nrecommended as follow-up — out of scope for a CI-green remediation and would be a\nredesign. Verification: see the containers-iac re-run result recorded on commit.\n\n### 5. secrets — Gitleaks 2 generic-api-key FPs\n\nReproduced locally over the main-run range (`43da320..HEAD`) → 2 findings, both the\n`idempotency_key=\"a\"` test-fixture pattern (`tests/integration/test_usage_export_endpoint.py:117`\nand a security-report line quoting it). Verified FPs (test idempotency keys, not\nsecrets). It passed on PR #4 because a PR scans only base..HEAD (fixtures are in an\nancestor commit); on main the push range included the fixtures' commit (bcf16bb). Fix:\ncommitted `.gitleaks.toml` — extends the full default ruleset (`[extend] useDefault =\ntrue`) + ONE allowlist requiring BOTH the two fixture paths AND an `idempotency_key=`\nline regex (condition = AND), so it's not a blanket path disable. Causality verified\nlocally: same range → 2 findings without the config, 0 with it, exit 0.\n\n### 6. codeql — literal placeholders\n\n`.github/workflows/pipeline-ci.yml` had literal `<CODEQL_LANGUAGE>` /\n`<CODEQL_BUILD_MODE>` in the matrix → the init step always failed. Filled `python` /\n`none` (interpreted language; Python 3.12-only build). Not a required context but it\nwas flapping.\n\n### Hygiene\n- Added `.terraform/` + `.terraform.lock.hcl` + `.coverage.*` to `.gitignore`;\n  `infra/.terraform/` and the local `.coverage.*` pid files are NOT committed.\n- `terraform fmt` reverted on 4 files it touched only cosmetically (data/edge/prod/\n  staging) that I made no functional change to — kept the diff scoped to the 3 modules\n  I actually changed (compute, network, observability) + the data module RDS/secret\n  edits.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":627,"cache_read_input_tokens":235393,"output_tokens":4195,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":627},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":4195,"cache_read_input_tokens":235393,"cache_creation_input_tokens":627,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":627,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcsojULyTQnsph6TBBAVL","attributionAgent":"debugging","type":"assistant","uuid":"ed937906-ddf9-4fa8-8a37-638de5df114b","timestamp":"2026-07-10T05:15:31.596Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"ci-fix/required-checks-green"}
